Friends and family are paying tribute to the late South African academic and gender activist, Rhoda Kadalie. Kadalie passed away in the US at the age of 68. She was SA’s human rights commissioner from 1995 until her widely publicised resignation in December 1997. Author Ryland Fisher, spoke on her legacy. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Academic, gender activist and former SA Human Rights Commissioner, Rhoda  Kadalie, has died aged 68. She passed away in Los Angeles in the US, where she’s been staying with her daughter. Her brother, Bruce, announced through Facebook that Kadalie died a few hours ago. Kadalie was SA’s human rights commissioner from 1995 until her widely publicised resignation in December 1997. READ: Racism is not always direct - Zulaikha Patel In 1999 she founded Impumelelo Social Innovations Centre, which promoted improving poor people’s quality of life. She’s also founder of the Gender Equity Unit at the University of the Western Cape. Kadalie was also a columnist for different newspapers. She shocked many when in 2016 she came out in support of controversial former US president, Donald Trump. At the time Kadalie said Trump’s victory was "good for the world". She was born in Cape Town’s District Six.